import os
import shutil

# Source folders
original_train_dir = r"C:\BISMI\COURSE\AI\Fundamental_ML_Programming_new\Assignments\Lab3\archive (6)\train\train"
original_test_dir = r"C:\BISMI\COURSE\AI\Fundamental_ML_Programming_new\Assignments\Lab3\archive (6)\test\test"

# Creating new small dataset folder
base_dir = './data_small'
train_dir = os.path.join(base_dir, 'train')
cat_dir = os.path.join(train_dir, 'cats')
dog_dir = os.path.join(train_dir, 'dogs')

if not os.path.exists(base_dir):
    os.makedirs(cat_dir)
    os.makedirs(dog_dir)

    cat_images = [f for f in os.listdir(original_train_dir) if f.startswith('cat')][:2500]
    dog_images = [f for f in os.listdir(original_train_dir) if f.startswith('dog')][:2500]

    for fname in cat_images:
        shutil.copy(os.path.join(original_train_dir, fname), os.path.join(cat_dir, fname))

    for fname in dog_images:
        shutil.copy(os.path.join(original_train_dir, fname), os.path.join(dog_dir, fname))

sample_dog_imgs = os.listdir(dog_dir)[:5]

EDA Summary

The dataset contains 2500 cat and 2500 dog images — perfectly balanced.¶
  • Most images are colored (RGB) and have varying sizes.
  • Average size is roughly around 200x200 pixels, but we'll standardize this to (150, 150) during preprocessing.
  • Images appear diverse in breed, lighting, and background — a good challenge for a model

from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

# Using the already resized data folder: './data_small/train'
IMG_SIZE = (150, 150)
BATCH_SIZE = 32

datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255, validation_split=0.2)

train_generator = datagen.flow_from_directory(
    './data_small/train',
    target_size=IMG_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary',
    subset='training',
    shuffle=True
)

val_generator = datagen.flow_from_directory(
    './data_small/train',
    target_size=IMG_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='binary',
    subset='validation',
    shuffle=False
)

In [21]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Flatten, Dense, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import ModelCheckpoint
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Defining model
cnn_model = Sequential([
    Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(150, 150, 3)),
    MaxPooling2D(2, 2),
    Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    MaxPooling2D(2, 2),
    Flatten(),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

cnn_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Save best model
checkpoint_cnn = ModelCheckpoint("cnn_best_model.h5", save_best_only=True, monitor='val_accuracy', mode='max')

# Train
cnn_history = cnn_model.fit(
    train_generator,
    epochs=10,
    validation_data=val_generator,
    callbacks=[checkpoint_cnn]
)

# Plot training history
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
plt.plot(cnn_history.history['accuracy'], label='Train Accuracy')
plt.plot(cnn_history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Val Accuracy')
plt.title('Custom CNN - Training & Validation Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

print("3.1 Custom CNN model trained. Best version saved as 'cnn_best_model.h5'.")

2.Fine-Tune VGG16 (pre-trained on imagenet). Make sure to use validation to test for over-fitting. Plot the appropriate graph (3 points)¶

In [22]:
from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras.layers import GlobalAveragePooling2D

# Loading VGG16 base
base_vgg = VGG16(include_top=False, input_shape=(150, 150, 3), weights='imagenet')
base_vgg.trainable = False  # Freeze base

# Adding custom head
vgg_model = Sequential([
    base_vgg,
    GlobalAveragePooling2D(),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
])

vgg_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Save best VGG16 version
checkpoint_vgg = ModelCheckpoint("vgg_best_model.h5", save_best_only=True, monitor='val_accuracy', mode='max')

# Train
vgg_history = vgg_model.fit(
    train_generator,
    epochs=10,
    validation_data=val_generator,
    callbacks=[checkpoint_vgg]
)

# Plot training history
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
plt.plot(vgg_history.history['accuracy'], label='Train Accuracy')
plt.plot(vgg_history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Val Accuracy')
plt.title('VGG16 - Training & Validation Accuracy')
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

print("3.2 Fine-tuned VGG16 model trained. Best version saved as 'vgg_best_model.h5'.")

from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix, precision_recall_curve, average_precision_score
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Loading best models
cnn_model.load_weights("cnn_best_model.h5")
vgg_model.load_weights("vgg_best_model.h5")

# Prediction on validation set
val_generator.reset()
cnn_preds = cnn_model.predict(val_generator).flatten()
vgg_preds = vgg_model.predict(val_generator).flatten()

y_true = val_generator.classes
y_pred_cnn = (cnn_preds > 0.5).astype(int)
y_pred_vgg = (vgg_preds > 0.5).astype(int)

# --- Accuracy ---
cnn_acc = np.mean(y_pred_cnn == y_true)
vgg_acc = np.mean(y_pred_vgg == y_true)

print(f"4.1 Accuracy:\n- CNN Accuracy: {cnn_acc:.4f}\n- VGG16 Accuracy: {vgg_acc:.4f}")

# PR Curve
def plot_pr_curve(y_true, y_score, label):
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_score)
    ap = average_precision_score(y_true, y_score)
    plt.plot(recall, precision, label=f"{label} (AP = {ap:.2f})")

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plot_pr_curve(y_true, cnn_preds, "CNN")
plot_pr_curve(y_true, vgg_preds, "VGG16")
plt.xlabel("Recall")
plt.ylabel("Precision")
plt.title("Precision-Recall Curve")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

from tensorflow.keras.utils import array_to_img

val_generator.reset()
misclassified_idx = np.where(y_pred_vgg != y_true)[0]

# Showing 10 random misclassified samples
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))
for i, idx in enumerate(np.random.choice(misclassified_idx, 10, replace=False)):
    batch_idx = idx // val_generator.batch_size
    img_batch, label_batch = val_generator[batch_idx]
    img = array_to_img(img_batch[idx % val_generator.batch_size])
    true = int(label_batch[idx % val_generator.batch_size])
    pred = int(vgg_preds[idx] > 0.5)
    
    plt.subplot(2, 5, i + 1)
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.title(f"True: {true}, Pred: {pred}")
plt.suptitle("4.5 VGG16 Misclassified Examples", fontsize=16)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

5. Add your conclusions. (3 point)¶

Model Comparison:

  • Custom CNN: ~75% accuracy; overfits after a few epochs.
  • VGG16 (Fine-tuned): ~90% accuracy; excellent generalization and high average precision.

Observed Errors:

  • CNN misclassified many dogs as cats.
  • VGG16 errors were mostly on visually confusing or ambiguous images.

Recommendations:

  • Fine-tune more VGG16 layers.
  • Use data augmentation.
  • Try stronger regularization or ResNet-based models.

Insight: Fine-tuning a pretrained network like VGG16 provides much better results than training a small custom CNN from scratch.
